<font color="#FF0000">REPLY TO CONNIE'S REQUEST</font><br>
<tt>Tue May 20  1:42:56 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Connie,<br>
1. My name is Gerald Ney.  I went to Vietnam as a 2nd Lt in Military Intelligence, making 1st Lt while there.  I was in charge of an aerial imagery interpretation section, and also flew on 39 hand held aerial photography missions.  In addition, spent a good deal of time on court martial duty.  For a more complete bio, check under the &quot;FORUM&quot;.<br>
2. Well, if I had my druthers, I would rather have gone to Germany.  In the aerial imagery business, working with cutting edge satellite and SR-71 imagery was done in the DC area or in Germany, keeping an eye on the Russians and the Warsaw pact.  Only a third of my class went to Vietnam.  As for why did I think I had to go; the surface answer is I was an officer and had my orders.  Underneath, while I had some doubts, at that time I still thought the &quot;domino&quot; theory was a good rationale.<br>
     I don't think we have space for them all... a little old woman with a bloody bandage almost bigger than her around her middle, who had been caught in a crossfire between the VC and us, being gently interrogated... the unbelievably small pile of ashes left after a chopper crashed with a full load of rockets and fuel due to a maintainance screwup... the changes in the fields during the rice growing cycle... many faces above olive drab uniforms... the Australian shower... world class sunrises and sunsets... skimming over the terrain at treetop level...  kids dashing into the road to get the candy bars Maj. Shivers tossed from his jeep... rust colored dust in and on everything during the dry season... green mold everywhere during the monsoon... acres of hot peppers on the low hills near Phu My... the sound of choppers warming up for an alarm clock... Vietnamese beer and ice cream, a possibly acquired taste... endless beaches... the nightly mortaring... and others, some a bit private.<br>
4. Yes, came to believe our jumping into the war was a mistake, that we really didn't know what we were doing.<br>
5. Treated fine by family and friends.<br>
6. Personally, I came out more mature and aware of both my strengths and weaknesses.  Most of what I am now was set during my time there.  As for the country, my views are pretty much what they became during my year in Vietnam.<br>
7. We've learned to be more careful about sticking our neck out, sometimes to the point of being gunshy.  We've learned to question government and authority on all points, and have become less trustful of each other.  In other words, I believe we've carried our &quot;lessons&quot; to the opposite extreme in many case or haven't always learned the right lessons.  The Army learned &quot;muzzle the press&quot; for instance.  We really won't know for sure what we've learned though until we go through a crisis of the same magnitude.
<p><code>-- gerald_ney@icpphil.navy.mil  (Gerald Ney, &quot;professor&quot;, 7/68-7/69) </code><p>


